<ul>
  <li>
    <p>HW Dump</p>

    <p>Choose any two short stories from the selections I‚Äôve uploaded to
  Canvas. Alternatively, I would approve another short story selection
  from one of the authors I‚Äôve included (Vonnegut, Butler, Nemisin) if you talk to me first.</p>

    <p>Give a general comparison of the two pieces you‚Äôve read. What
  standsout out to you thematically in each piece? What lesson, or moral,
  does each text offer? Try and describe the ideals, ethics, or sense of
  morality the story deploys so that you (the reader) can tell right from
  wrong in the context of these speculative fictions. Feel free to quote
  directly from the readings if that helps you explain your ideas.</p>

    <p>Kurt Vonnegut - Welcome to the Monkey House</p>

    <ul>
      <li>The town doesn‚Äôt like new people</li>
      <li>First sentence - ‚ÄúThe year was 2081, and everybody was finally equal‚Äù
        <ul>
          <li>Leads to one of the first characters mentioned having ‚Äòaverage intelligence‚Äô. Because Harrison was average, his parents didn‚Äôt think about it very much</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>making everyone equal only pushed people down with the average</li>
      <li>Referring to the time that people always competed the ‚Äòdark ages‚Äô
        <ul>
          <li>Both Hazel and George agreed that it was good to have these limitations</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Even though an announcer was terrible at his job, Hazel (who represents average society) thinks that he should get a raise because he tried so hard.</li>
      <li>Harrison was seen as dangourus because he was a ‚Äògenuis‚Äô and an ‚Äòathlete‚Äô</li>
      <li>‚ÄúNow watch me become what I can become!‚Äù (pg. 12)</li>
      <li>‚ÄúThe music began again and was much improved‚Äù (pg. 13)
        <ul>
          <li>By allowing there to be competition, people are able to fulfill their full potential and therefore play better than if there were no competition</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>30 foot ceilings - represent their potential and every time they jumped, they got closer to that potential until they finally kissed it</li>
      <li>They were later shot by the Hadicapper General and everyone forgot about it.
        <ul>
          <li>It‚Äôs hard to go against society</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>Jemisin - The Elevator Dancer</p>

    <ul>
      <li>A girl dancing alone in an elevator, doesn‚Äôt care about anything else going on</li>
      <li>Has free thought and is allowed to admire this girl‚Äôs free spirit</li>
      <li>Realization that he lives an empty life
        <ul>
          <li>One that is fully controlled by a strict government</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>A lot of religious mentions. The society is governed by what is seen as holy</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

