<h3 id="mla">MLA</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Avoid plagerism</li>
  <li>Shows off the research you‚Äôve done</li>
</ul>

<p>Professor uses TurnItIn (orginality report)</p>

<ul>
  <li>Avoid plagirism</li>
  <li>Professor only cares if it‚Äôs above 10% shared material</li>
  <li>Make sure to do proper citations (TurnItIn is picky)</li>
</ul>

<p>If you are citing a source, try to get as close to the primary source as possible.</p>

<h3 id="sources">Sources</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Who wrote it?</li>
  <li>Where is it?</li>
  <li>When was it written?</li>
</ul>

<p>MLA Cared how you found certain information.</p>

<h3 id="how-to-use-mla">How to Use MLA</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Start with the formatting
    <ul>
      <li>Font, style, spacing, alignment</li>
      <li>Margins, Headers, Heading</li>
      <li>Hanging indent for Works Cited</li>
      <li>Short works vs. Long works
        <ul>
          <li>Short Works (ex. article, chapters, songs, poems, etc.) are part of a larger text and you put quotations around them</li>
          <li>Long works can be broken down further and you put them in Italics</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>Make sure the header is also in Times New Roman 12pt font</p>

<p><strong>Heading</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>Student name</li>
  <li>Professor‚Äôs name</li>
  <li>Class</li>
  <li>Date</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="how-to-cite-images">How to Cite Images</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Underneath
    <ul>
      <li>Caption: authors last name, title, create description</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 id="footnotes-try-not-to-use-them">Footnotes (Try not to use them)</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Only for bibliagraphic information or if you‚Äôre providing vital historical information (however, you should have this part of the actual paragraph)</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="in-text-citation">In-Text Citation</h3>

<ul>
  <li>At the end of the sentence(s) of information (NOT at the end of the paragraph)</li>
  <li>If you‚Äôre using the same source, cite it every 3 sentences</li>
  <li>You might want to work the author‚Äôs name into the sentence (narrative citation)</li>
</ul>

<p>No class on Monday</p>
<h1 id="lecture-13---final-profile-draft-10-14-20">Lecture 13 - Final Profile Draft (10-14-20)</h1>

<h3 id="1st-page-formatting">1st Page Formatting</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Times New Roman, 12pt</li>
  <li>Heading, Header, title, paragraph (indent)</li>
  <li>0.5 inch indent, 1 inch margins</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="pictures">Pictures</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Side by side if you have two images in a row</li>
  <li>Caption
    <ul>
      <li>‚Äú[Figure x:] description + citation‚Äù</li>
      <li>Font Arial 8-10pt font</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 id="in-paragraph-features">In Paragraph Features</h3>

<ul>
  <li>In text citation
    <ul>
      <li>(LAST NAME pg#/para. #) ‚Üê actually write ‚Äúpara.‚Äù if it‚Äôs a paragraph</li>
      <li>(‚ÄúTItle of Source (or first few words)‚Äù para. #)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Don‚Äôt use surface level sources</li>
  <li>Always cite sources
    <ul>
      <li>Nothing is assumed to be true</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 id="paraphrasesummerizing">Paraphrase/Summerizing</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Basic Statistics</li>
  <li>When wording doesn‚Äôt matter</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="quote">Quote</h3>

<ul>
  <li>The original phrasing matters</li>
  <li>Short quotes are more useful (a long quote is 3+ lines of text; everything should be shorter than that)</li>
  <li>Don‚Äôt need an in text citation for one word quotes when you note the author</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="before-you-turn-in">Before You Turn In</h3>

<ul>
  <li>Make sure there are no comments or suggestions</li>
  <li>Make sure to have your name on the final document
